{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd5a6658-6ff2-4c5d-b0c3-32d44abb1f25","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively with its own `--treenode-filter` syntax. To filter by class name:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter follows a `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>` hierarchy — the `*` wildcards match any assembly and namespace, narrowing to just the `SmsNotificationTests` class (2 tests: `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a9413d32-04e7-43e3-a6d5-80c1b4f45def","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively, not VSTest. The filter syntax for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` with a specific syntax.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, to filter by class name, the syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit v0.6.120 — this is a relatively recent version. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively.\n\nWith `dotnet test`, TUnit projects that use MTP can be run. But the filter syntax depends on whether we're using VSTest compatibility or native MTP.\n\n\nSince the csproj shows `OutputType` as `Exe` with no VSTest runner enabled, this confirms it's a pure MTP project. The treenode filter uses a path-like format with segments for assembly, namespace, class, and test name, so filtering by class would follow the pattern `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests`.\n\nWith `dotnet test` on .NET 9+, I need to pass MTP-specific arguments after `--`, so the command becomes `dotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"` to isolate just that test class.","outputTokens":659,"requestId":"1BC4:F3EF4:22F0E7C:26983DE:6A03D6F8"},"id":"2338d946-258e-4774-a031-c74c712397f9","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:42:30.636Z","parentId":"f1099d1e-261e-40a8-ba5c-b0236a8545bd"}
